FBIS3-25859 "drchi021_b_94002" FBIS-CHI-94-021 Document Type:Daily Report 1 Feb 1994 United States & Canada President Clinton Urges Progress in Talks With Japan OW3101230094 Beijing XINHUA in English 2232 GMT 31 Jan 94 OW3101230094 Beijing XINHUA Language: English Article Type:BFN [Text] Washington, January 31 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton called Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa last night and urged progress in the U.S.-Japan economic framework talks, the White House said here today. The President has sent U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor and deputy assistant to the President for economic policy Bo Cutter to Tokyo to meet with their Japanese counterparts, said White House press secretary Dee Dee Myers at a news briefing. They will hold consultations to "seek mutually agreeable resolutions to the issues being discussed under the framework," Myers said. President Clinton and Prime Minister Hosokawa are scheduled to meet in Washington on February 11. In last night's call, Clinton also extended to Prime Minister Hosokawa his congratulations on achieving political reform in Japan. Both houses of Japanese parliament have passed a package of anti-corruption bills put forward by Prime Minister Hosokawa. "The President thinks it is a good step that the government has resolved this and can move forward now to focusing on economic issues," Myers said.
